## Session Start

When starting a session, read `.planning/STATE.md` for current position,
recent decisions, and open items. This orients you without requiring a
full context re-read of the codebase.

If context compacts mid-session: preserve current task context in STATE.md
before compaction completes. After compaction, re-read `.planning/STATE.md`
to restore orientation. Hooks handle this automatically — focus on keeping
STATE.md accurate.

## Two Systems

This project uses two complementary systems for continuity:

**instruction system** (static, human-curated) — defines HOW to work:
- `CLAUDE.md` — project identity and behavioral guidance
- `.claude/rules/` — conventions, session protocol, guardrails
- `.claude/settings.json` — tool permissions and hook configurations
- `.claude/hooks/` — automated session-start and session-end behavior

**learning system** (dynamic, session-updated) — captures WHAT is happening:
- `.planning/STATE.md` — current position, decisions, open items (shared via git)
- Auto memory — user preferences and cross-session insights (machine-local)

Instructions stay stable across sessions. State evolves with each session.

---

## Auto Memory

Keep auto memory under 200 lines. Use an index + topic pattern to stay organized:
save a short index entry per topic and expand only when needed. Prefer
`.planning/STATE.md` for critical project state — STATE.md is shared via git,
auto memory is machine-local and not visible to collaborators.

Note: `autoMemoryDirectory` and `autoMode` must be set in user or local settings,
not project settings (`.claude/settings.json`). Project settings are shared via git
and cannot safely carry machine-specific paths.

